In Java, a "protected" concept refers to a type of access modifier that can be used to control the accessibility of a member variable or method within a class.

When a class defines a member variable or method as "protected", it means that the variable or method can be accessed by any class that inherits from the defining class, as well as by any object of the defining class.

For example, if we define a class called "Animal" with a protected method called "makeSound", any subclasses of "Animal" can access and override this method, as well as any objects of the "Animal" class itself. This is because "protected" members are accessible within the package that the class is defined in, as well as by any subclass or object of the defining class.

Here is an example of a class with a protected method:
```java
class Animal {
    protected void makeSound() {
        System.out.println("Animal is making a sound.");
    }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    @Override
    protected void makeSound() {
        System.out.println("Dog is making a sound.");
    }
}
```
In this example, the "Animal" class has a protected method called "makeSound", which can be accessed and overridden by any subclass of "Animal", including "Dog". The "Dog" class also has its own implementation of the "makeSound" method, which is overriding the protected method defined in "Animal".

In summary, the protected keyword in Java is used to control the accessibility of members within a class, allowing them to be accessed by any subclass or object of the defining class, as well as within the package that the class is defined in.

