Go currently does not support generic types, so it's not possible to write a generic "map" function that can operate on any type of slice. However, you can write a function that uses the `reflect` package to map over slices of any type.

Here's an example of a generic "map" function that can operate on slices of any type:

```
package main

import (
    "reflect"
)

func Map(slice, function interface{}) interface{} {
    sliceValue := reflect.ValueOf(slice)
    functionValue := reflect.ValueOf(function)
    result := reflect.MakeSlice(sliceValue.Type(), sliceValue.Len(), sliceValue.Cap())

    for i := 0; i < sliceValue.Len(); i++ {
        input := []reflect.Value{sliceValue.Index(i)}
        output := functionValue.Call(input)
        result.Index(i).Set(output[0])
    }

    return result.Interface()
}
```

