`mtsamples` is a variable that stores the number of samples in a dataset. When working with machine learning models in MATLAB, it is often useful to know the size of the dataset, including the number of samples and features. `mtsamples` is a convenient way to access this information.

In the code you provided, `mtsamples` is used as the size of the input matrices `X` and `y`. This ensures that the model is trained on all samples in the dataset, and not just a subset of them.

For example, in the following code, `mtsamples` is used to ensure that the size of the input matrix `X` is the same as the number of samples in the dataset:
```python
% Load dataset
load fisheriris

% Split dataset into training and testing sets
cv = cvpartition(species, 'HoldOut', 0.3);
training_set_idx = cv.training;
testing_set_idx = cv.test;

% Extract features and target variable from training and testing sets
X_train = meas(training_set_idx,:);
y_train = species(training_set_idx);
X_test = meas(testing_set_idx,:);
y_test = species(testing_set_idx);

% Normalize input features
X_train = normalize(X_train);
X_test = normalize(X_test);

% Train model
mdl = fitcknn(X_train, y_train, 'NumNeighbors', 3);

% Use trained model to make predictions on testing set
y_pred = predict(mdl, X_test);
```
In this code, `mtsamples` is used to determine the number of features to extract from the dataset. The `meas` function is used to extract the features from the dataset, and the resulting matrix `X_train` has the same number of rows as `mtsamples`, which is the number of samples in the training set.
